{
  "doc_id": "7887",
  "text": "Somewhat mirroring the finding that one specific D-type cyclin, CCND3, regulates proliferation in dark zone B cells [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , the anti-apoptotic protein myeloid cell leukaemia 1 (MCL1) has recently been identified as the principal regulator of B cell survival in GC formation [CITATION_3] . By contrast, BCL-XL was dispensable in this context [CITATION_4] . The conditional deletion of Mcl1 early after immunization (at day 2) prevented the formation of GCs, which suggests a continuous requirement for MCL1 throughout the entire GC initiation phase [CITATION_5] , which is similar to the requirement for MYC. It will be interesting to determine the mechanism underlying the specific dependency of GC B cells on MCL1.",
